  h2.under 1/ Your content must be good enough to be its own product
  p You're competing against literally billions of blog posts, videos, podcasts etc.
  p And it’s winner takes all. The top 1% that gets 99% of the attention.
  p Michelin wrote!{' '}
    span.italic the guide
    |!{' '}for motorists.
  p Whoever wrote the 2nd best guide didn't get half the attention.
  h2.under 2/ If in doubt, teach your customers
  h2.under 3/ Your content should be easy to sum up
  h2.under 3/ Sray the course
  p e.g. Every single day one hundred thousand people watch Angela from Planterina talk about plants. Two years ago that number was one thousand.
  h2.under 4/ Don't make content you don't promote
  p Once you've got a reputation word-of-mouth kicks in. But no-one starts with a reputation.
  p So you're wasting great content on 10 Twitter followers. Promot
  //- p I invested $200 to get my Twitter account off the ground.
  h2.under 5/ Create the type of content your customers consume
  p Basecamp is a project management tool for startups. Startup people read books. So Basecamp wrote a load of books.
  p It's that simple.
